<div class="note-source" id="TSJN-01-07-0475-sn">
<p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipient's copy ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ The National Archives ]">DNA</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Papers of the Continental Congress ]">PCC</span>, No. 86); in a clerks hand except for final phrase of complimentary close and signature, in De Thulemeiers hand; endorsed by Humphreys: Hague Jany. 24. 1785 from The Baron Thulemeier Covering Observations of the K. of Prussia on the draught of a Treaty, &amp;c. <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ transcript ]">Tr</abbr> (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ The National Archives ]">DNA</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Papers of the Continental Congress ]">PCC</span>, No. 116); in Humphreys hand. Covering letter and enclosure were forwarded by Commissioners to Jay in theirs of 18 Mch. 1785 as enclosures Nos. 3 and 4. English translation of De Thulemeiers letter is in <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789</span>, <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">i</span>, 5534. Enclosure (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ The National Archives ]">DNA</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Papers of the Continental Congress ]">PCC</span>, No. 86, p. 95120, in the same hand as that of the clerk who copied De Thulemeiers letter, and with notations by Benjamin Franklin, as indicated below) contains the French translation of the treaty-project and the observations written in parallel columns; for convenience they are here printed in sequence.</p>
  <p>In referring to <a id="TSJN-01-07-0475-kw-0001" class="keywordref" title="jump to notre projet in text" href="#TSJN-01-07-0475-ks-0002">notre projet</a> and, for example, <a id="TSJN-01-07-0475-kw-0002" class="keywordref" title="jump to notre article viii in text" href="#TSJN-01-07-0475-ks-0007">notre article viii</a>, De <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="TSJN-01-07-02-pb-0628">[628<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=TSJN/Pages/TSJN-01-07/TSJN-01-07-02-pb-0628.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span> Thulemeier is, of course, referring to the earlier proposal which Adams had made to him in Mch. 1784 and which employed the text of the Swedish treaty as its basis (De Thulemeier to Adams, 14 Mch. and 9 Apr. 1784, the second of which enclosed the text of what is here referred to as <a id="TSJN-01-07-0475-kw-0003" class="keywordref" title="jump to notre projet in text" href="#TSJN-01-07-0475-ks-0002">notre projet</a>; all in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Massachusetts Historical Society, Boston ]">MHi</span>: Adams Manuscript Trust). Accordingly, the present text is referred to by De Thulemeier as the <a id="TSJN-01-07-0475-kw-0004" class="keywordref" title="jump to contre-projet in text" href="#TSJN-01-07-0475-ks-0001">contre-projet</a>. In view of these preceding negotiations and because he regarded Adams as a personal friend, De Thulemeier wrote to him on this same day about the observations du Roi sur le Contre-Projet du Trait de Commerce, qui ma t remis de Votre part au mois de Novembre de lanne dernire and added: Agres quen qualit de votre ancien Collgue, toujours reconnaissant de lamiti que vous mavez temoigne pendant votre sjour  la Haye, je prenne la libert de vous parler avec quelque franchise. Les Observations sur les articles 2, 3, 4, 5, 8, 10, et 12 du Contre-projet sont envisages a Berlin comme trop essentielles pour quon puisse se dpartir des changemens et additions proposs. Je ne vous dissimulerai point mme, Monsieur, qua en juger par mes Instructions la Conclusion du Trai en dpendra selon toute apparence. Les remarques postrieures contribueront uniquement  donner plus de clart et de prcision  quelques articles. Daigns, Monsieur, envisager tout ceci non comme une dclaration Ministrielle mais simplement comme un tmoignage de ma confiance et du dsir dont je suis anim dassurer le succs de nos soins communs et dloigner tout ce qui pourrait faire natre des obstacles trop essentiels pour que je puisse esprer de les surmonter. Un mot de rponse de votre part me ferait grand plaisir (De Thulemeier to Adams, 24 Jan. 1785, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Massachusetts Historical Society, Boston ]">MHi</span>: Adams Manuscript Trust). <a id="TSJN-01-07-0475-kw-0005" class="keywordref" title="jump to Nos reponses aux observations de Mr. Adams  au mois de mai in text" href="#TSJN-01-07-0475-ks-0901">Nos reponses aux observations de Mr. Adams  au mois de mai</a>: These were the observations mentioned by Adams in his letter to the president of Congress of 7 June 1784; De Thulemeiers letter to Adams and the observations enclosed therein are to be found in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Massachusetts Historical Society, Boston ]">MHi</span>: Adams Manuscript Trust under 6 June 1784; Adams letter and his observations are in <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789</span>, <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">i</span>, 45863.</p></div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#TSJN-01-07-0475-fn-0001-ptr" id="TSJN-01-07-0475-fn-0001">1</a>
<p>The words et sans etre  cargaison are bracketed and underscored in <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ manuscript (arbitrarily applied to most documents other than letters) ]">MS</abbr> and the following is written beneath this passage in Benjamin Franklins hand: Omit these lines if the proposd Addition is allowd. For the proposd Addition see the Observations under Article <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">viii</span>.</p></div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#TSJN-01-07-0475-fn-0002-ptr" id="TSJN-01-07-0475-fn-0002">2</a>
<p>At this point in <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ manuscript (arbitrarily applied to most documents other than letters) ]">MS</abbr> there is a caret and, in the adjoining column, a corresponding symbol followed by this notation in the hand of Benjamin Franklin: which Compensation, in Case of Dispute, shall be determined by Arbitrators mutually chosen from among the Merchants of a neutral Nation.Query if some such Addition as the above may not answer the Objection?</p></div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#TSJN-01-07-0475-fn-0003-ptr" id="TSJN-01-07-0475-fn-0003">3</a>
<p>The words To be considerd are written in Franklins hand just above this Article in the column containing Observations.</p></div>
